ed in the Book of Judith in the Apocrypha. Judith is portrayed as a beautiful widow who delivers her people from the invading Assyrians by gaining the confidence of their commander, Holofernes, and cutting off his head while he is asleep; without their commander, the Assyrians are duly routed. This has been a perennially popular Jewish name. In the English-speaking world it was taken up in the 16th century, having been in occasional use among Gentiles before this: for example, it was borne by a niece of William the Conqueror. It enjoyed great popularity between the 1940s and the 1960s. Today's notable bearers include the American novelist  Judith Krantz  (  b. 1928 ) and the Scottish composer  Judith Weir  (  b. 1954 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Judeth had at least 1 daughter with William Mallett."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1414–Male":"1414–Surnud","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"Surnud","1437":"1437","1414":"1414","1542":"1542","Chilham, Kent, England":"Chilham, Kent, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1414–Male":"1414–Kuollut","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"Kuollut","1437":"1437","1414":"1414","1542":"1542","Chilham, Kent, England":"Chilham, Kent, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1414–Male":"1414–Décédé","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"Décédée","1437":"1437","1414":"1414","1542":"1542","Chilham, Kent, England":"Chilham, Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Judeth a eu au moins 1 fille avec William Mallett."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1414–Male":"1414–Verstorben","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"Verstorben","1437":"1437","1414":"1414","1542":"1542","Chilham, Kent, England":"Chilham, Kent, England","lifeSummary":"Judeth hatte mit William Mallett mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","1414–Male":"1414–Desede","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"Desede","1437":"1437","1414":"1414","1542":"1542","Chilham, Kent, England":"Chilham, Kent, England"},"hu":{"–":"elhunyt","1414–Male":"1414–elhunyt","1437–1542":"1437–1542","–Female":"elhunyt","1437":"1437","1414":"1414",